<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-336-316  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 336 316.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  June 12 1989 v35 n1762 p13(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Debate role of government in consortiums.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Barrett, Joyce.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>American Enterprise Institute Dir of Science and TechnologyStudies Claude Barfield and Ralph E. Gomory, former senior vicepresident for science and technology at IBM, disagree on whethergovernment support of high-technology consortiums should includepost-development production.andP;  Gomory is of the opinion thatgovernment-supported consortiums aid research and development andspeed up the time to market process.andP;  Barfield maintains thathigh-technology companies would come up with their own money ifthe government did not offer it first.andP;  Barfield was extremelycritical of cooperative research arrangements between industries,universities and the government.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     High technologyGovernment FundingResearch and DevelopmentUnited States. Congress. Joint Economic CommitteeConsortia.andO;Person:    Gomory, Ralph E. (attitudes); Barfield, Claude (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>